programme.title: Ill Manors
programme.desc: A drug dealer returns to his London council estate after 15 years in prison, which sets in motion a chain of violent events that impacts on the lives of various residents struggling to survive in the community, including a small-time crook torn between his morals and his loyalty to his ruthless friend. Crime drama, starring Riz Ahmed, Nick Sagar and Keith Coggins.

programme.title: Breakfast
programme.desc: A round-up of national and international news, plus sports reports, weather forecasts and arts and entertainment features. Presented by Ben Thompson.

programme.title: Match of the Day
programme.desc: Gary Lineker presents highlights of the latest Premier League matches, including Arsenal v Chelsea at the Emirates Stadium and Liverpool v Crystal Palace at Anfield. Both league fixtures between the Gunners and the Blues last season ended in draws, including a 2-2 result on this ground. However, Maurizio Sarri's side overcame Unai Emery's men 3-2 in this season's reverse fixture at Stamford Bridge, thanks to goals from Pedro, Alvaro Morata and Marcos Alonso. Plus, action from Bournemouth v West Ham United at the Vitality Stadium, Manchester United v Brighton & Hove Albion at Old Trafford, Newcastle United v Cardiff City at St James' Park, Southampton v Everton at St Mary's Stadium, Watford v Burnley at Vicarage Road and Wolverhampton Wanderers v Leicester City at Molineux.

programme.title: The Andrew Marr Show
programme.desc: A round-up of the week's stories, featuring interviews with key figures in politics and current affairs and a round-up of the Sunday papers. Including news and weather at 10.00.

programme.title: Sunday Politics
programme.desc: The latest political news and debate from a regional perspective.

programme.title: The Big Questions
programme.desc: Nicky Campbell presents moral and religious discussions on topical issues live from Appleton Academy, Bradford.

programme.title: Homes Under the Hammer
programme.desc: Martin Roberts and the team explore properties about to be auctioned, then talk to the buyers about their plans for the buildings.

programme.title: Songs of Praise
programme.desc: Rev Kate Bottley goes open water swimming to explore the links between faith and fitness and there is a performance by Christian singer-songwriter Jenn Bostic.

programme.title: Lifeline
programme.desc: Nick Knowles presents an appeal on behalf of Walking with the Wounded, a charity which helps vulnerable veterans integrate back into society and sustain their independence.

programme.title: Porridge
programme.desc: Prison-based comedy from writers Dick Clement and Ian La Frenais, who penned the initial series aired in the 1970s. Cyber criminal Fletch has taken to helping his fellow inmates with appeals and letters home to loved ones, but finds things become complicated when cellmate Barry's girlfriend pays a visit. Kevin Bishop stars as Nigel ?Fletch' Fletcher, grandson of original offender Norman Stanley.

programme.title: Bargain Hunt
programme.desc: The antiques show comes from Wetherby racecourse, West Yorkshire, where experts David Harper and Philip Serrell offer advice to two teams trying to find items they can sell at auction. Presenter Tim Wonnacott also visits Harewood House.

programme.title: Money for Nothing
programme.desc: Sarah Moore is in Altrincham hoping to find some hidden gems she can transform and send off to a new home. Meanwhile, Bex Simon almost meets her match with a filing cabinet.

programme.title: Escape to the Country
programme.desc: Jules Hudson is on a house-hunting mission in the Somerset countryside with a keen gardening couple who have £700,000 pounds, and hopes of enjoying the county's mild climate.

programme.title: Pointless Celebrities
programme.desc: Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman invite another selection of celebrities from the world of radio broadcasting to take part in the unorthodox quiz show. As ever, success can only be achieved by guessing the least likely correct answers to questions posed to members of the public. This time, Mark Steel teams up with Marcus Brigstocke, Nicky Campbell partners Rachel Burden, Liz Kershaw allies with DJ Nihal, and Shaun Keaveny joins forces with Nemone.

programme.title: Countryfile
programme.desc: Anita Rani tastes a local cheese with a long heritage in Wiltshire, where Matt Baker discovers the incredible work of a care farm that is changing children's lives. Paralympian Hannah Cockroft is in the Highlands of Scotland meeting a young gamekeeper to find out what the job entails and Tom Heap investigates how far people are prepared to go to keep the UK's farms free from disease. Including Weather for the Week Ahead.

programme.title: Antiques Roadshow
programme.desc: Fiona Bruce presents the show from Crathes Castle, Aberdeenshire, where finds brought in to be valued include a collection of signed Harry Potter books, ornate silver from Iona, a German art deco figurine, an intricate Italian bracelet, and a baseball cap with an unusual story to tell.

programme.title: Call the Midwife
programme.desc: Lucille treats an elderly hoarder (Annette Crosbie) suffering from a malodorous leg ulcer, and fears that living surrounded by towering piles of rubbish, books and tins of food will have a serious effect on her recovery. Sister Hilda has a challenging case on her hands when a family newly arrived from Ghana are found to be suffering from an unidentified illness, and Violet runs for a place on the local council, but Fred is not convinced she can make a difference to the community, placing more faith in the Civil Defence Corps.

programme.title: Les Miserables
programme.desc: Cosette has grown into a teenager, and to Valjean's dismay, questions her closeted life and is desperate for a new start in Paris. The opportunity presents itself when she meets Pontmercy's son Marius, who has turned his back on his family after learning the truth about his father, and now lives in a squalid tenement, where he catches the eye of the daughter of a criminal family. Javert ascends through the ranks of the police, and believes he is closing in on his goal.

programme.title: Match of the Day 2
programme.desc: Mark Chapman reviews the day's Premier League action, introducing highlights of Huddersfield Town v Manchester City and Fulham v Tottenham Hotspur. The relegation-threatened Terriers conceded six goals against the champions early in the season, and had only won one of their last 11 home games in this fixture. At Craven Cottage, Claudio Ranieri's men faced a Spurs side that had triumphed on their last four visits. There's also a round-up of all the goals from Saturday's eight games, including Arsenal v Chelsea.

programme.title: Jonathan Pie's American Pie
programme.desc: Spoof documentary in which a bumbling British reporter is sent across the Atlantic to get the inside scoop on the US midterm elections.

programme.title: Breakfast
programme.desc: Dan Walker and Louise Minchin present a round-up of national and international news, plus current affairs, arts and entertainment, and weather.

programme.title: Rip Off Britain: Holidays
programme.desc: Gloria Hunniford, Julia Somerville and Angela Rippon looking at some of the things that can go wrong on cruises, while Simon Calder has tips on dealing with long-haul flights.

programme.title: Homes Under the Hammer
programme.desc: Martin Roberts, Martel Maxwell and Dion Dublin follow the progress of properties sold at auction in Shropshire, Derby and Cumbria.

programme.title: Wanted Down Under
programme.desc: Nathaniel Baker believes his family's future lies in Australia, but wife Gemma sees things very differently, so they check out properties, work opportunities and life in Melbourne.

programme.title: Caught Red Handed
programme.desc: A shop worker is horrified when a knife-wielding man bursts into his store, leaving him with seconds to make the most important decision of his life.

programme.title: Bargain Hunt
programme.desc: Mark Stacey and Gary Pe help two teams find items at Stamford Meadows in Lincolnshire, while presenter Natasha Raskin Sharp also visits the Stamford Mercury News Archive.

programme.title: Doctors
programme.desc: Zara reaches breaking point with Daniel and presents him with an unusual proposition, while Karen and Valerie fish for gossip when a visitor turns up with a surprise for Mrs Tembe.

programme.title: Father Brown
programme.desc: Mallory is forced to turn to the sleuthing priest for help when a senior member of the police force is murdered at a bowls match. Fifties-set crime drama, starring Mark Williams.

programme.title: Escape to the Country
programme.desc: Jonnie Irwin heads to the Perth and Kinross countryside to help a couple relocating from Dundee with a £550,000 budget. He also visits the British School of Falconry at Gleneagles.

programme.title: The Farmers' Country Showdown
programme.desc: Goat's milk ice-cream producers Ian and Lauren and cider-makers Shawn and Trudie compete with the weather and the FIFA World Cup at the Great British Food Festival.

programme.title: Antiques Road Trip
programme.desc: Experts Anita Manning and Paul Laidlaw set off on a search for items around the Trossachs in Stirlingshire, buying a spoon, a stool and a soda syphon along the way.

programme.title: Pointless
programme.desc: Quiz in which contestants try to score the fewest points possible by giving the least obvious correct answers to questions. Presented by Alexander Armstrong, with Richard Osman.

programme.title: The One Show
programme.desc: The first visit of the week to the One Show studio, where Matt Baker and Alex Jones present the usual mix of topical stories and celebrity chat.

programme.title: Inside Out
programme.desc: Documentary series focusing on regional stories of interest.

programme.title: EastEnders
programme.desc: Kat revels in looking after her kids, while Stacey worries about Hayley. Mick is still feeling down and refuses to speak to Johnny over the phone, only for his day to go from bad to worse when football mum Megan to arrive, complaining that the team has folded. As the two find themselves at loggerheads, the landlord quickly realises he is fighting a losing battle.

programme.title: Panorama
programme.desc: An official inquiry has found that more than 450 patients had their lives shortened at Gosport War Memorial Hospital in 1990s, with many being given fatal doses of painkillers even though they were not terminally ill and had only been admitted for rehabilitation following routine operations. Reporter Richard Bilton investigates the evidence and challenges those who may be to blame for the deaths.

programme.title: Silent Witness
programme.sub-title: To Brighton, to Brighton - Part One
programme.desc: Part one of two. During a heatwave in Brighton, the Lyell team is summoned to a waste dump where a body part has been found. The search is on to recover the other dismembered remains and piece together the victim's body, which is covered in intricate Japanese tattoos. Away from the lab, Nikki has some news that she desperately wants to share with Matt, but must wait until he visits from America. Forensic crime drama, starring Emilia Fox, David Caves, Richard Lintern and Liz Carr, with Samantha Bond.

programme.title: Imagine
programme.desc: Alan Yentob follows the British playwright, whose award-winning work takes audiences to the very heart of the defining political events that shape all our lives. The film delves into Graham's acclaimed hits including This House, Labour of Love and Ink, alongside his recent Channel 4 drama Brexit: The Uncivil War, while also exploring his own personal story and what drives him to create such unique political theatre.

programme.title: The Graham Norton Show
programme.desc: The host welcomes triple Oscar-nominated Laura Linney, who is returning to the London stage in the critically acclaimed My Name Is Lucy Barton. Actress Saoirse Ronan talks about playing the title role in new movie Mary Queen of Scots, while rising star Timothee Chalamet discusses his powerful addiction drama Beautiful Boy. Plus, Stephen Mangan reflects on his Sky Arts series Portrait Artist of the Year, the 1975 perform It's Not Living (If It's Not with You), and another bunch of intrepid audience members steps up to the plate, willing to recount an anecdote from the dreaded red chair.(n)

programme.title: Breakfast
programme.desc: A round-up of national and international news, plus current affairs, arts and entertainment, and weather, presented by Dan Walker and Louise Minchin.(n)

programme.title: Rip Off Britain: Holidays
programme.desc: Gloria Hunniford, Julia Somerville and Angela Rippon investigate the sunshine resort that suddenly started turning away guests. Plus, a guide to experiencing the Northern Lights.(n)

programme.title: Homes Under the Hammer
programme.desc: Dion Dublin visits houses in Stourbridge and Liverpool, and there is a look at a property in Brentwood, Essex that Martin Roberts first saw back in 2016.(n)

programme.title: Wanted Down Under
programme.desc: Matthew and Zelease Ballentine-Brain fly out to Melbourne for a trial week to check out the property, work and lifestyle they could have if they moved to Australia permanently.(n)

programme.title: Caught Red Handed
programme.desc: A shop owner risks her life to save a colleague from an armed robber wielding an axe. Elsewhere, two teenagers steal a life size ornamental pig.(n)

programme.title: Bargain Hunt
programme.desc: In Berkshire, a team of men and a team of women are challenged to scour an antiques fair at Newbury racecourse seeking bargains to sell for profit at auction. Trusty experts Natasha Raskin and Mark Stacey guide the competitors around the fair, while Tim Wonnacott travels to Winchester Cathedral in Hampshire to investigate its celebrated West Window.(n)

programme.title: Doctors
programme.desc: Al decides he is the best person to help Alia with her future plans, while Mrs Tembe and Gordon put on a show when they realise they are being spied on.(n)

programme.title: Father Brown
programme.desc: The amateur sleuth struggles to protect those closest to him when an old foe is unexpectedly released from prison.(n)

programme.title: Escape to the Country
programme.desc: Alistair Appleton heads to the Welsh Borders to help a couple with a budget of £775,000 find a countryside home to raise their young son and establish a glamping retreat business.(n)

programme.title: The Farmers' Country Showdown
programme.desc: Alpaca farmers Ian and Caroline, and former circus ringmaster-turned-farmer Drew, compete with their alpacas for coveted red rosettes at the Royal Three Counties Show.(n)

programme.title: Antiques Road Trip
programme.desc: Paul Laidlaw and Anita Manning visit the Islands and Lowlands of Scotland. Paul uncovers a festive antique, while Anita is caught by the gaze of a former Lord Provost of Kilmarnock.(n)

programme.title: Pointless
programme.desc: Quiz in which contestants try to score the fewest points possible by giving the least obvious correct answers to questions. Presented by Alexander Armstrong, with Richard Osman.(n)

programme.title: The One Show
programme.desc: Another mix of nationwide reports and live studio-based chat, hosted by Matt Baker and Alex Jones.(n)

programme.title: EastEnders
programme.desc: Alfie feels the pressure as Ian has to withdraw his investment and Kat berates him for not fulfilling his promises. Desperate for cash, he seeks out Phil and makes him an offer. Kush is surprised to see Denise back from her mini-break, Mick asks Mitch to try again with the football team and Keanu is suspicious when Phil asks him to work discreetly on a car.(n)

programme.title: Holby City
programme.sub-title: A Daring Adventure or Nothing At All
programme.desc: Frieda is happy that her life is back on an even keel, but her contentment is shattered when ex-boyfriend Roman unexpectedly reappears. With their relationship going well, Zav is keen to step up and ease the burdens weighing on a stressed Donna. But all does not entirely go to plan when he embarks on some impromptu parenting of Mia. Ange feels the pressure as she works to sell her vision for her Young Adult Unit while treating a difficult and vulnerable patient.(n)

programme.title: Silent Witness
programme.sub-title: To Brighton, to Brighton - Part Two
programme.desc: Part two of two. With the remains of a second tattooed victim appearing in a Brighton recycling plant, it seems the Lyell team is on the trail of a serial killer. Working closely with local detectives DI Taramelli and DS Quicke, they must painstakingly piece together the evidence, and unearth the connections between a diverse range of suspects.(n)

programme.title: Have I Got a Bit More News for You
programme.sub-title: Have I Got a Bit More Old News for You
programme.desc: Not Going Out star and Would I Lie to You? team captain Lee Mack takes over the reins for extended edition of the satirical quiz, with broadcaster Janet Street-Porter and comedian Sara Pascoe joining team captains Ian Hislop and Paul Merton to poke fun at the stories making the headlines in April 2018.(n)

programme.title: Stacey Dooley in the USA
programme.sub-title: Stacey Dooley in the USA: Kids in the Crossfire
programme.desc: The presenter travels to Chicago, which has been dubbed the `murder capital of America', where almost half of the people killed in 2013 were under 25. She meets the Hardmons who are struggling to come to terms with the murder of their 19-year-old daughter Ashley, who was caught in the crossfire of a gang shooting. Stacey also travels to a prison boot camp for young offenders and meets a teenager who received his first gun at 14, and has already been jailed four times. Last in the series.(n)

programme.desc: Coverage of the conclusion of the final from Alexandra Palace, London, where the first player to reach 10 frames will win the Paul Hunter Trophy. programme.title: Icons: The Greatest Person of the 20th Century
programme.desc: Sanjeev Bhaskar assesses the legacies and achievements of Mohandas Gandhi, Helen Keller, Martin Luther King Jr and Emmeline Pankhurst - four of the 20th century's greatest activists. Gandhi employed non-violent tactics to help secure independence for India, while the deaf and blind Keller used her fame to fight for the rights of marginalised people everywhere. King was arguably the most influential figure of the black civil rights movement in the US, while Pankhurst was a controversial figure in the fight for women's suffrage.

As nurse Heather deals with Christine's demands, Colin arrives followed by Michelle and Alan and the ensuing group discussion leaves Christine very worried about her chances of survival. Comedy, starring Elaine C Smith.

programme.desc: Michael Portillo explores British Columbia, steered by his Appleton's Guide to Canada, published in 1899. He discovers how two superpowers nearly came to war over a pig and joins the Royal Canadian Navy to firefight on board the frigate HMCS Regina. Starting on Vancouver Island, the largest island on the Pacific coast of North America, Michael explores the rich British heritage and colonial past of the provincial capital of British Columbia, Victoria.(n)

programme.title: Celebrity Antiques Road Trip

programme.sub-title: Matr, Pilgrim, Blue Caribou Canteen - New International
programme.desc: Fred Sirieix oversees a battle for investment between three people who think their take on new international dining will secure them the backing needed to open on the high street. First, they must pitch to four of the industry's leading investors for the opportunity to open for business in Manchester. Amongst those pitching is married couple Jonas Lorentzen and Naina Gupta, who want to bring Michelin style Nordic cuisine to the UK. Going up against them are three industry friends - Jamie Duffield, Dave Bone and Anthony Power - whose restaurant idea is inspired by the Camino de Santiago pilgrimage through Portugal and Spain.(n)

programme.title: Icons: The Greatest Person of the 20th Century
programme.desc: Clare Balding assesses the legacies and achievements of Pele, Muhammad Ali, Billie Jean King and Tanni Grey-Thompson - four of the 20th century's greatest sport stars. Brazilian footballing legend Pele showed the world that anyone, from any background, could become the world's most renowned sportsperson - if they had the talent - while Ali's boxing skill and charisma secured the love of his fans, but his attitudes towards race, religion and America's role in the Vietnam War all challenged society and meant he was hated by others. As well as being one of the best tennis player of all time, King was also a tireless campaigner for equality. She fought for prize-money parity, was instrumental in the first women's professional tennis tour and founded the Women's Tennis Association. Grey-Thompson was born at a time when the physical and political landscape for disabled people was far from enlightened, and became one of Britain's most successful paralympians.(n)

programme.title: Tennis: Australian Open
programme.sub-title: Tennis: Australian Open Highlights: 2019 Day Eight
programme.desc: Kat Downes presents action from day eight of the Grand Slam, featuring the concluding fourth-round singles matches at Melbourne Park. programme.title: Icons: The Greatest Person of the 20th Century
programme.desc: Sanjeev Bhaskar assesses the legacies and achievements of Mohandas Gandhi, Helen Keller, Martin Luther King Jr and Emmeline Pankhurst - four of the 20th century's greatest activists. programme.desc: Michael Portillo explores British Columbia, steered by his Appleton's Guide to Canada, published in 1899. programme.title: My Million Pound Menu
programme.sub-title: Matr, Pilgrim, Blue Caribou Canteen - New International
programme.desc: Fred Sirieix oversees a battle for investment between three people who think their take on new international dining will secure them the backing needed to open on the high street. First, they must pitch to four of the industry's leading investors for the opportunity to open for business in Manchester. Amongst those pitching is married couple Jonas Lorentzen and Naina Gupta, who want to bring Michelin style Nordic cuisine to the UK. Going up against them are three industry friends - Jamie Duffield, Dave Bone and Anthony Power - whose restaurant idea is inspired by the Camino de Santiago pilgrimage through Portugal and Spain.(n)

programme.title: Icons: The Greatest Person of the 20th Century
programme.desc: Clare Balding assesses the legacies and achievements of Pele, Muhammad Ali, Billie Jean King and Tanni Grey-Thompson - four of the 20th century's greatest sport stars. Brazilian footballing legend Pele showed the world that anyone, from any background, could become the world's most renowned sportsperson - if they had the talent - while Ali's boxing skill and charisma secured the love of his fans, but his attitudes towards race, religion and America's role in the Vietnam War all challenged society and meant he was hated by others. As well as being one of the best tennis player of all time, King was also a tireless campaigner for equality. She fought for prize-money parity, was instrumental in the first women's professional tennis tour and founded the Women's Tennis Association. Grey-Thompson was born at a time when the physical and political landscape for disabled people was far from enlightened, and became one of Britain's most successful paralympians.(n)

programme.desc: Documentary following volunteers from the Bat Society, who patrol the country rescuing the flying mammals from the most unlikely places and getting injured ones fit enough to be released back into the wild.(n)

programme.sub-title: Tennis: Australian Open Highlights: 2019 Day Seven

programme.title: Ski Sunday

programme.title: Live Snooker: The Masters
programme.desc: Coverage of the conclusion of the final from Alexandra Palace, London, where the first player to reach 10 frames will win the Paul Hunter Trophy. Both players were battling it out for their maiden Triple Crown title in last year's showpiece match, and it was Northern Ireland's Mark Allen who prevailed 10-7 against Kyren Wilson of England. Little could separate the two players until Allen moved 6-5 ahead before notching a break of 119 in the next. Wilson rallied to pull it back to 8-7, but his opponent was able to respond to become the first man from his country to win the title since Dennis Taylor in 1987 and collected a £200,000 prize for his efforts.

As word of their actions spreads, other refugees join them to form a larger resistance movement. However, one of the brothers fears their struggle is doomed. Second World War drama, starring Daniel Craig, Liev Schreiber and Jamie Bell.

Brazilian footballing legend Pele showed the world that anyone, from any background, could become the world's most renowned sportsperson - if they had the talent - while Ali's boxing skill and charisma secured the love of his fans, but his attitudes towards race, religion and America's role in the Vietnam War all challenged society and meant he was hated by others. As well as being one of the best tennis player of all time, King was also a tireless campaigner for equality. She fought for prize-money parity, was instrumental in the first women's professional tennis tour and founded the Women's Tennis Association. Grey-Thompson was born at a time when the physical and political landscape for disabled people was far from enlightened, and became one of Britain's most successful paralympians.(n)

programme.sub-title: The Lastest Gun in the West

programme.sub-title: The Old Man and the Key

programme.desc: Premiere. The long-suffering youngster hopes his lifelong run of bad luck will come to an end when he develops a crush on a new schoolfriend. When the princess is a teenager with 70-foot long tresses, she escapes with the aid of a bandit and goes in search of her home, but the witch is not going to let her go without a fight. Disney animated comedy based on the Rapunzel story, with the voices of Mandy Moore and Zachary Levi.

programme.title: Wonders of the Universe
programme.desc: Professor Brian Cox continues his exploration of the origins of mankind by investigating the matter from which everything on Earth is formed. At a Hindu cremation in Nepal, he discusses the faith's philosophy of life as an eternal cycle of creation and destruction, and draws a parallel with the lives of the universe's stars - before revealing why everything on Earth was once a part of something else.

programme.title: Orbit: Earth's Extraordinary Journey

programme.title: Is Anybody Out There
programme.desc: A rundown of developments in the search for extraterrestrial intelligence, exploring the theory that life was `seeded' on Earth by asteroid impacts in the remote past, and speculating on the possibility of inhabited planets existing elsewhere in the universe. Nasa officials share their thoughts on whether Jupiter's moon Europa is capable of supporting micro-organisms, while more far-sighted scientists look beyond the solar system, stressing that space knows no boundaries - and neither do the possibilities it contains.

programme.title: The Secret Life of the Sun
programme.desc: Using satellite images and the expertise of Britain's leading solar scientists, Kate Humble and Helen Czerski investigate the inner workings of the star and the influence its cycles of activity have on Earth. They reveal the sun is more active now than it has been for a decade, sending out super-heated plasma and waves of radiation, and examine why some experts think longer-term changes in its behaviour may have powerful effects on the world's climate.
